  "prompt": "Phrases: Where did the term \"phoning it in\" come from, and how did it come to mean someone not trying hard enough?",
  "response": "The phrase \"phoning it in\" originated in the entertainment industry, particularly in the early days of radio and television. Back then, performers who were unable to appear in person due to scheduling conflicts or other reasons would sometimes deliver their lines or performances over the phone. This approach was often seen as less engaging or sincere compared to an in-person performance, as the physical presence and energy of the performer were absent.\n\nOver time, the phrase evolved to describe any situation where someone is putting in minimal effort or not fully committing to a task. It conveys a sense of detachment or indifference, suggesting that the person is just going through the motions without truly caring or investing themselves in the work. The phrase has since become a common way to critique someone for not trying hard enough or for delivering a subpar effort.",
